there are three redirects in Linux
1. standart input (stdin) : it has file desriptor number as 0
2. standart output (stdout) : it has file desriptor number as 1
3. standart error (stderr) : it has file desriptor number as 2


1. output(stdout) -1
by default when running a command its output goes to terminal
the output of command can be routed to a file.
ls -l > listings.txt
if using the same file for additional output
pwd >> listings.txt

2. input(stdin) -0
input is used when feeding file contents to a file
cat < listings.txt

3. Error(stderr) -2
we can use redirects to route errors from the screen
ls -l /root 2>errorFile
telnet locakhost 2> errorfile
